	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I'm currently modifying an NES for this very purpose. However I'm soldering wires. I'm also modifying a 60-72pin adapter as well. Unfortunatly my adapter has the expansion port pins left off so I'm going to have to use an external cable instead of doing it the easy way. I'd probably give making my own cartridge adapter a shot but who knows where to get those parts. 
<br />
<br />I did discover that in order to use an external sound source, say the output of a CD player, you not only have to ground it properly, but you have to put a 100 ohm resister between the ground and the audio output. I'm not sure if this is required or not for famicom carts but if it is that's not a problem. I can do it. Without the resistor it's bairly audible. Of course this mixes with the standard NES audio so unless you're developing some sort of external NES device for storing games then this information isn't worth much. 
<br />
<br />I don't understand why american game developers didn't take advantage of the extra sound input on the expansion port and the fact that you can access it from the cartridge slot. A simple jumper pack on the expansion port and they could have used enhanced music on their NES games. 
<br />Heck they could have included an enhanced sound chip on the pack and it would have worked as well. No more complicated than installing the expansion pack on the N64 really.
<br />
<br />By the way, if you haven't found a way yet, I can provide the music for Castlevania 3. let me know.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


